It's a pretty good ramen! Very tasty for sure. I don't like that they have a mandatory tip when they bring the bill. I always tip, but I do it according to the type and level of service. Bringing me a plate with soup involves barely any service. But hands down it was a good Ramen.

Discovered this Japanese Food Court at Waikiki yesterday, and I was walking around observing the texture of the ramen noodles and this place convinced me. The three things that I am extremely picky about are (A.) dumplings (B.) ramen and (C.) sponge cakes. So you know when I say it's good, it should be pretty reliable. First of all, the noodles did not disappoint. It didn't taste like the package noodles, but rather the hand pulled ones. Because of the thickness, it kinda reminds me of the Northern hand pulled noodles. I ordered the cold noodles because of the weather and also cause the noodle wouldn't get soggy so quickly. The broth is a bit tangy than I like but it's perfect for this heat. It's less filling that way.  Finally, the pork was flavorful and tender. Overall, I think this bowl of ramen is better than any ramen I had in Tokyo. I will try the traditional broth ramen next time when I return to Hawaii. . P.S. be prepared to drink a gallon of water afterward. It WILL make you super thirsty after.  price: $15 USD (CASH ONLY) taste: 3.8 / 5 atmosphere: ⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️ seating: ⭐️⭐️⭐️ Price Performance ratio: 3.8 / 5

The noodles have a bouncy type of chew, and the broth was so flavorful. Definitely drop by if you like Tsukemen!

The negi green onion on the top was pretty spicy, was seasoned with salt and pepper and sesame oil. They have fresh garlic which is added after the half.  It was very good combination. They also have homemade hot chili. That was pretty spicy, but I liked it.

This ramen place is located in Waikiki Yokocho or Japanese food hall. I came here with my husband on a Sunday night and place was pretty busy. We weren't super hungry so we didn't mind the wait. We wrote our names down on the wait list and waited around 10 minutes.  Things to note: Cash Only and no take-out.  There isn't a variety of broths offered. It's mainly just tonkotsu. We ordered fried chicken and 2 bowls of regular egg ramen.  Fried chicken was juicy and tasted pretty good -4/5  Ramen: broth was thick and had a rich flavor. But I just thought it was a bit too oily for me. I added some fresh garlic and spicy powder that was tasty and not too spicy. I wasn't a fan of the thick noodles and prefer thin noodles, but that's my preference. The pork chashu was sliced thick and was really good. However, 2 out of the 3 slices I had were mainly fat, so I didnt eat my last slice because it was just too rich. My husband though had nice meaty slices in his bowl. He really loved the bowl of ramen he received.  Because we weren't super hungry, we couldn't finish all the fried chicken and I didn't finish my bowl. I couldn't take it to-go to eat it at my hotel. Overall I give this place 3 stars for both food and experience.

I would like to start by saying that I know ramen well. We spent 2 weeks in Japan mostly eating ramen. It is also our comfort food at home and we live in a city with fantastic ramen options.  This ramen is not good. The broth has almost no flavor and this is the core of a good ramen. It doesn't taste like it was cooked for many hours like it's supposed to be.  The broth is also overly fatty with lots of visible fat floating in the broth which isnt very appetizing to see. It is amazing that even with this much fat they managed to get almost no flavour into the broth. The meat had an odd flavour that it really shouldn't have from the marinade that they use and is mostly fat (almost no actual meat). If this was cheap fast ramen I might let it slip and give it a 3 but it's expensive for what it is and isnt good. I left more than half of my bowl because I just couldn't bring myself to finish it. If you want good ramen please go elsewhere, there are much better options in Waikiki.

Cash only. Their tsukemen was really good and filling. Broth was delicious. Noodles are firm. Service was great and fast.

We ordered the special Ramen. The broth was too fatty, though the meat and the noodle were good. Actually the noodle was very good considering many Ramen restaurants in the US serve noodle that feels like instant noodle.

The dipping ramen is probably the best ramen I've had outside of Japan. The acidic vinegar base of the soup cuts through the fattiness of the meat, and really stimulates your appetite. The noodles are also springy and perfectly sized, pushing me to get a second order of just the noodles. The sprouts provided a delightful crunch, a fantastic counterbalance to the noodles. The house spice was also pleasantly hot, yet not so much as to overwhelm the palate.  So why only three stars?  First is the traditional ramen (soy based broth with the noodles in the broth) that others in my party had gotten. The broth was so overly salty and fatty that it was virtually inedible. Later we noticed that some around us had ordered the traditional ramen with 50% salt, something that I strongly STRONGLY suggest. However, that still doesn't address the fattiness of the broth (yes I know ramen broth is often thicker and richer, but this was to an extreme)  That leads into point number two, which was the chashu. Traditionally, the chashu is beautiful layers of fat with lean meat. However, the monstrosities in ALL of our bowls was all fat (you can see it in the picture). All that gristle was what made the traditional ramen unbearably fatty. It was only tolerable in the dipping ramen because it was cut through by the vinegar base broth.  Third was the ajitsuke tamago (or ramen egg). This was absolutely nothing like fantastically gooey and delectable eggs that I had in Japan. They seemed almost like de-shelled hard boiled eggs that were dropped into the soup right beforehand.  It's too bad, because I badly want to go back again for that incredible dipping ramen.

(Original) 日本で食べたことがないので比較は出来ませんが、帰国したら新橋に行きたいと思うほど美味しかったです。 オススメの食べ方で食べて正解でした。 滞在中に何度かラーメンを食べましたが、ここが一番美味しく満足出来ました。厨房は日本人のスタッフさんでした。 ガッツリとしていて量の多く脂も多いので好みは分かれるでしょうが、私は最高だと思います。 ニンニクは絶対に入れた方が良いです！ 特製唐辛子もオススメです！ 書いてある通りに食べてみてあとはお好みで。 けっこうニンニクの匂いが残りますが。。。  新橋本店も行ってみたいですね。

Holy Moly this is good food!  Incredibly simple menu - we ordered the regular Ramen.  It comes with vegetables and tender pork piled on top, and the noodles and broth are just phenomenal!  It’s in the basement of a high-rise, and mixed up between a bunch of other Japanese themed restaurants, but don’t miss it because it was wonderful food.  I loaded mine up with their Ramen sauce (a soy based dark sauce), and hot peppers (hot hot hot!).  It was good as it was served, and phenomenal after I spiced it up.  I hear the “dipping noodle” is too heavy - I don’t know as I didn’t try it.  The basic Ramen is the way to go!  I usually go to Ramen Nakamura, but it’s too fancy for my kids.  This place was a great alternative.  They had a high chair for my littlest, and didn’t mind the mess they made (kids and Ramen...).  Highly recommend!

I would've given 5 stars if the drink selection was a bit better. Only Asahi and Pepsi. But holy amazing food!!! Exactly what you need after a 10+hour flight!!!  *Pro-tip go before 6pm. Very small place that gets wildly crowded. (Extra tip- don't shy away from the garlic n spice.... it's your mouth best friend. Put some in your date’s ramen too. Then, Kissing with garlic breath won’t be an issue.

The taste balls are salty. ■ The price is about 20 dollars (tax + tip) for Ajitama ramen, but this is Hawaii.  (Original) ■二郎系のラーメン ■日本なら並で食べられない程の量なんですが、ここでは Regular で丁度良い量で、普通に美味しくいただきました。 ■麺は太麺で硬め、チャーシューはトロトロで美味し。味玉はしょっぱい。 ■値段は味玉ラーメンで約20ドル(税+チップ)は高いが、ここはハワイ。

Wow! Good ramen restaurant. It’s in a Japanese food hall, toward the back, and on the right. They only take cash so make sure you bring it. Their prices range from about 12-19 dollars for ramen. They have a few appetizers also. Their noodles used in their ramen are super thick, about halfway from a normal ramen noodle to a udon noodle. Their noodles are al dente which makes it delicious. Their broth is rich and yummy. They add cabbage and the broth is pretty garlicy. They have two sizes: regular and large. Their regular is busting with noodles and other things. It was huge and I couldn’t even finish it! Also, they are super friendly! Overall, a really good ramen place.
Oishi! Top favorites are the pork-based broth ramen and chashu don! A must!
Cash only and 15% off for locals.  Very solid bowl of ramen noodles although the broth is a little too fatty for me.
(Translated by Google) Excellent tsukemen!  (Original) Excellent tsukemen!
They offer 10% off at certain times. Broth is rich and tasty. Noodles are thick and perfectly cooked, nearly the same in size as udon. Overall good bowl and would come again.
